While I'd feel comfortable using a driverless car, 'cause I don't drive, myself. 
I'm wondering what the future of them is. 
Will there only be companies such as Waymo using them as taxis?
Or, will the public be able to buy and use them?
Will the software that runs these cars be included in the price?
Or, will it be a subscription kind of thing to keep them on the road?
I can see them becoming very handy.
But, I can also see them becoming a very expensive nuisance.  
I can see companies charging a king's ransom to use them, *cough* apple, adobe *cough*.

The biggest reason I don't feel comfortable with self driving cars is because they take away the democratization of owning a car. Now, any dumbass can learn to repair an internal combustion engine. Self driving cars are extremely complex machines that only a handful of people in the planet are equipped to maintain and repair. If they were to become ubiquitous,  that would lend itself very easily to monopolies. It's the same thing Apple does with the iPhone. Only they can fix it and they can charge you up the ass if they want to.

but how can you implement this in society though? do we need another subscription to some company that is made to make a profit? this is another move towards a future where no one owns anything anymore? I love the technical stuff that makes this possible, however i do think there needs to be a debate towards how we are going to use such a system? to me personally this should become like public transport, where most of it is owned or partially owned by the government. So the company does not get to much power in out transport(i.e. increasing the prices when everyone has sold their cars). 
only time will tell if we allow such a company to become another amazon or apple or if we handle it in such a way everyone can profit from it not just the rich.

Derek, as an avid pilot, I believe that you have very underestimated what the pilots do inside of a jet aircraft, by your definition the plane could be monitored from the ground and there would be no need for pilots at all, so why would we have them? There is more to flying a plane than VFR (Visual Flight Rules), there is also what most higher trained pilots use which is called IFR (Instrument Flight Rules) Where the pilot doesn't need anything at all outside of their 6 main instruments and the radio to fly and land a plane effectively, one bad apple out of a lot of hundreds of thousands of pilots that fly daily is more P hacking than flying fact

"Under perfect conditions" is an important caveat, especially considering how much of the Earth is still rural. People say it will take 10+ years because it is much easier for AI to be accurate and precise in good conditions, but extremely difficult to train it for unexpected or atypical conditions. That is why things like image interpreters can be really good for objects with large data sets but still completely misread situations a human would understand easily (ex. apple and pen separately are fine, but sticking an apple full of pens can be confusing). One could argue that this technology could improve at an accelerated rate due to advancements in technique and processing power, but I would argue there is a limit to modern-day styles of machine learning that result in heavily decreased returns as it approaches such a high level of intelligence, even for companies specializing in it, like Google/Alphabet. Something major will have to change for it to be rolled out outside of bigger cities and that could very well take 10 years.
